# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: industrial-control-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] An **air gap**, **air wall**, **air gapping** or **disconnected network** is a network security measure employed on one or more computers to ensure that a secure computer network is physically isolated from unsecured networks, such as the public Internet or an unsecured local area network.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] It means a computer or network has no network interface controllers connected to other networks, with a physical or conceptual air gap, analogous to the air gap used in plumbing to maintain water quality.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] An *air-gapped* computer or network is one that has no network interfaces, either wired or wireless, connected to outside networks.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Many computers, even when they are not plugged into a wired network, have a wireless network interface controller (WiFi) and are connected to nearby wireless networks to access the Internet and update software.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] This represents a security vulnerability, so air-gapped computers have their wireless interface controller either permanently disabled or physically removed.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] To move data between the outside world and the air-gapped system, it is necessary to write data to a physical medium such as a thumbdrive, and physically move it between computers.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] It is easier to control than a direct full network interface, which can be attacked from an exterior insecure system and, if malware infects the secure system, can be used to export secure data.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] For this reason, some new hardware technologies are also available, like unidirectional data diodes or bidirectional diodes (also called electronic airgaps), which physically separate the network and transportation layers and copy and filter the application data.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] In environments where networks or devices are rated to handle different levels of classified information, the two disconnected devices or networks are referred to as *low side* and *high side*, *low* being unclassified and *high* referring to classified, or classified at a higher level.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] This is also occasionally referred to as *red* (classified) and *black* (unclassified).
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Access policies are often based on the Bell–LaPadula confidentiality model, where data can be moved low-to-high with minimal security measures, while high-to-low requires much more stringent procedures to ensure protection of the data at a higher level of classification.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] In some cases (for instance, in industrial critical systems), the policy is different: data can be moved from high to low with minimal security measures, but moving from low to high requires a high level of procedural safeguards to ensure the integrity of the industrial safety system.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] The concept represents nearly the maximum protection one network can have from another (save turning the device off).
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] One way to transfer data between the outside world and the air-gapped system is to copy data on a removable storage medium such as a removable disk or USB flash drive and physically carry the storage to the other system.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] This access still has to be carefully controlled since a USB drive may have vulnerabilities (see below).
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] The upside to this is that such a network can generally be regarded as a closed system (in terms of information, signals, and emissions security), unable to be accessed from the outside world.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] This is the reason that another way to transfer data, used in appropriate situations like critical industries, is to use data diodes and electronic airgaps, which assure a physical cut of the network by a specific hardware.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Sophisticated computer viruses for use in cyberwarfare, such as Stuxnet and Agent.BTZ have been designed to infect air-gapped systems by exploiting security holes related to the handling of removable media.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] The possibility of using acoustic communication has also been demonstrated by researchers.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Researchers have also demonstrated the feasibility of data exfiltration using FM frequency signals.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Limitations imposed on devices used in these environments may include a ban on wireless connections to or from the secure network, or similar restrictions on EM leakage from the secure network through the use of TEMPEST or a Faraday cage.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Despite a lack of direct connection to other systems, air-gapped networks have been shown to be vulnerable to attack in various circumstances.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Scientists in 2013 demonstrated the viability of air gap malware designed to defeat air gap isolation using acoustic signaling.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Shortly after that, network security researcher Dragos Ruiu's BadBIOS received press attention.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] In 2014, researchers introduced *AirHopper*, a bifurcated attack pattern showing the feasibility of data exfiltration from an isolated computer to a nearby mobile phone, using FM frequency signals.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] In 2015, BitWhisper, a covert signaling channel between air-gapped computers using thermal manipulations, was introduced.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] BitWhisper supports bidirectional communication and requires no additional dedicated peripheral hardware.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Later in 2015, researchers introduced GSMem, a method for exfiltrating data from air-gapped computers over cellular frequencies.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] The transmission - generated by a standard internal bus - renders the computer into a small cellular transmitter antenna.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] In general, malware can exploit various hardware combinations to leak sensitive information from air-gapped systems using "air-gap covert channels".
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] These hardware combinations use a number of different media to bridge the air-gap, including: acoustic, light, seismic, magnetic, thermal, and radio-frequency.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] From a security perspective, a major drawback of an air gapped network is the inability of software to automatically self update.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Users and system administrators must instead download and install updates manually.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] If a strict update routine is not followed, this results in out-of-date software running on the network, which may contain known security vulnerabilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] System administrators may manage software updates in an air gapped network using dedicated solutions such as Windows Server Update Services or network logon scripts.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] Such mechanisms would allow all computers on the air gapped network to automatically install updates after the system administrator downloads the updates from the Internet once.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] The problem is not completely eliminated, though, especially if users have administrative privileges on their local workstations and are therefore able to install software that is not centrally managed.
[src:industrial-control-security/air-gap-networking] The presence of IoT devices requiring firmware updates can also complicate matters, since often such updates cannot be centrally managed.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In the U.S., **critical infrastructure protection** (**CIP**) is a concept that relates to the preparedness and response to serious incidents that involve the critical infrastructure of a region or the nation.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The American Presidential directive PDD-63 of May 1998 set up a national program of "Critical Infrastructure Protection".
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In 2014 the NIST Cybersecurity Framework was published after further presidential directives.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] CIP is a national program to ensure the security of vulnerable and interconnected infrastructures of the United States.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In May 1998, President Bill Clinton issued presidential directive PDD-63 on the subject of critical infrastructure protection.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This recognized certain parts of the national infrastructure as critical to the national and economic security of the United States and the well-being of its citizenry, and required steps to be taken to protect it.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This was updated on December 17, 2003, by President George W.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Bush through Homeland Security Presidential Directive HSPD-7 for **Critical Infrastructure Identification, Prioritization, and Protection**.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The updated directive would add in agriculture to the list of critical infrastructure within the country; this would undo the omission of agriculture from the 1998 presidential directive.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Take, for example, a computer virus that disrupts the distribution of natural gas across a region.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This could lead to a consequential reduction in electrical power generation, which in turn leads to the forced shutdown of computerized controls and communications.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Road traffic, air traffic, and rail transportation might then become affected.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Emergency services might also be hampered.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] An entire region can become debilitated because some critical elements in the infrastructure become disabled through natural disaster.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] While potentially in contravention of the Geneva Conventions, military forces have also recognized that it can cripple an enemy's ability to resist by attacking key elements of its civilian and military infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The federal government has developed a standardized description of critical infrastructure, in order to facilitate monitoring and preparation for disabling events.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] With much of the critical infrastructure privately owned, the Department of Defense (DoD) depends on commercial infrastructure to support its normal operations.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Department of State and the Central Intelligence Agency are also involved in intelligence analysis with friendly countries.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] On March 9, 1999, Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre warned the United States Congress of a cyber terrorist "electronic Pearl Harbor" saying, "It is not going to be against Navy ships sitting in a Navy shipyard.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] It is going to be against commercial infrastructure".
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Later this fear was qualified by President Clinton after reports of actual cyber terrorist attacks in 2000: "I think it was an alarm.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] We lost our Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There are many examples of computer systems that have been hacked or victims of extortion.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One such example occurred in September 1995 where a Russian national allegedly masterminded the break-in of Citicorp's electronic funds transfer system and was ordered to stand trial in the United States.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] A gang of hackers under his leadership had breached Citicorp's security 40 times during 1994.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] They were able to transfer $12 million from customer accounts and withdraw an estimated $400,000.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In the past, the systems and networks of the infrastructure elements were physically and logically independent and separate.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] They had little interaction or connection with each other or other sectors of the infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] With advances in technology, the systems within each sector became automated, and interlinked through computers and communications facilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As a result, the flow of electricity, oil, gas, and telecommunications throughout the country are linked—albeit sometimes indirectly—but the resulting linkages blur traditional security borders.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] While this increased reliance on interlinked capabilities helps make the economy and nation more efficient and perhaps stronger, it also makes the country more vulnerable to disruption and attack.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This interdependent and interrelated infrastructure is more vulnerable to physical and cyber disruptions because it has become a complex system with single points of failure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In the past an incident that would have been an isolated failure can now cause widespread disruption because of cascading effects.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As an example, capabilities within the information and communication sector have enabled the United States to reshape its government and business processes, while becoming increasingly software driven.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One catastrophic failure in this sector now has the potential to bring down multiple systems including air traffic control, emergency services, banking, trains, electrical power, and dam control.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The elements of the infrastructure themselves are also considered possible targets of terrorism.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] For example, the 2022 attack on North Carolina’s power substations near Carthage leaving tens of thousands of residents without power.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The ordeal left residents without proper heating, hot water, and the ability to cook for days as repairs took place.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Authorities noted that the attack was intentionally committed via gunfire.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Traditionally, critical infrastructure elements have been lucrative targets for anyone wanting to attack another country.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Now, because the infrastructure has become a national lifeline, terrorists can achieve high economic and political value by attacking elements of it.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Disrupting or even disabling the infrastructure may reduce the ability to defend the nation, erode public confidence in critical services, and reduce economic strength.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Additionally, well chosen terrorist attacks can become easier and less costly than traditional warfare because of the interdependence of infrastructure elements.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These infrastructure elements can become easier targets where there is a low probability of detection.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The elements of the infrastructure are also increasingly vulnerable to a dangerous mix of traditional and nontraditional types of threats.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Traditional and non-traditional threats include equipment failures, human error, weather and natural causes, physical attacks, and cyber-attacks.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] For each of these threats, the cascading effect caused by single points of failure has the potential to pose dire and far-reaching consequences.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There are fears from global leaders that the frequency and severity of critical infrastructure incidents will increase in the future.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These infrastructure failures are prone to greatly affect the country’s residents who are on high alert.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One of these future potential failures can be seen within the cyber security world as American citizens fear that their technological infrastructure is at risk.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This comes as the world becomes more technologically advanced with the introduction of AI and technology into many areas of American life.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Although efforts are under way, there is no unified national capability to protect the interrelated aspects of the country's infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] One reason for this is that a good understanding of the inter-relationships does not exist.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There is also no consensus on how the elements of the infrastructure mesh together, or how each element functions and affects the others.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Securing national infrastructure depends on understanding the relationships among its elements as well as the immediate and delayed effects that these failures may have on residents.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Thus, when one sector scheduled a three-week drill to mimic the effects of a pandemic flu, even though two-thirds of the participants claimed to have business continuity plans in place, barely half reported that their plan was moderately effective.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These can have drastic effects on those who do not have access to the necessary safeguards in place to protect themselves.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Some of the most critical infrastructure for any in the US are the roads, hospitals, and infrastructure that provides food to residents.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] An increased risk of the collapse of these critical infrastructure points can lead to, and in most cases have led to, drastic decreases in access to water, food, medical attention, and electricity.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical needs for residents trapped in their homes and areas, residents who rely on medication or need to be transported to the nearest hospital, and residents who are heavily affected by malnutrition.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This was seen during the 2005 Hurricane Katrina aftermath in new Orleans as thousands were displaced, hundreds killed, and thousands more injured with no clear way of receiving shelter or assistance.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There is a current movement to improve critical infrastructure with residents in mind.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical infrastructure protection requires the development of a national capability to identify and monitor the critical elements and to determine when and if the elements are under attack or are the victim of destructive natural occurrences.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These natural occurrences have become more of a threat over the past couple of years due to climate change; increased occurrences of stronger storms, longer droughts, and rising sea levels.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] CIP's is importance is the link between risk management and infrastructure assurance.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] It provides the capability needed to eliminate potential vulnerabilities in the critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] CIP practitioners determine vulnerabilities and analyze alternatives to prepare for incidents.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] They focus on improving the capability to detect and warn of impending attacks on, and system failures within, the critical elements of the national infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] However, there are skeptics that see certain national infrastructure methods as harm to the communities that local and federal governments swore to protect.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This is a key factor in the movement against Atlanta’s “Cop City” as residents say that there are negative systematic affects as well as negative environmental affects as well.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Atlanta Public Safety Training Center, also known as, “Cop City” is one of the many examples of critical infrastructure created to try and serve the purpose of protecting the civilian populations.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This form of critical infrastructure is one that works indirectly as the project aims to train current and incoming police officers and combat units.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The plan is one that was put forth by the Atlanta Police Foundation in 2017 called the “Vision Safe Atlanta – Public Safety Action Plan.” This plan sees the police foundation receiving upgrades and attention to the crumbling infrastructure of police buildings and necessities throughout Atlanta.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The largest addition to the foundation and police force’s portfolio is about 85 acres of the city’s greenspace to construct a state-of-the-art training facility.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Atlanta Police Foundation is a private entity that works for the betterment of the city’s police force.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] According to the Atlanta Police Foundation, a private entity, the project has the backing of CEOs in the area along with public officials who not only have support for the foundation but support for the $90 million project which would lease and raze about 85 acres of publicly owned forests.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] According to… the center is being privately funded by other private entities with 2/3 of funding coming from private finance and the other third coming from taxpayer dollars.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These facilities include “a firing range, a burn building, and a ‘kill house’ designed to mimic urban combat scenarios”.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The overall goal of the facility is to ensure that Atlanta police officers are getting better training within the city whiles also getting a fresh space.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Although a positive outlook for the Police Foundation and the Atlanta Police Department, the facility has faced some pushback from the public in terms of the destruction of public land as well as police misconduct concerns.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Atlanta is a city that is surrounded by large and lush green foliage earning the title of a “a city in a forest” by residents and visitors; according to residents, the importance of the city’s forests cannot be understated.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] With such a large presence of trees and green space, residents see these spaces as a vital part of the city’s natural ecosystems.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Residents are concerned that the clearing of 85 acres of the forest will bring about an increase in poor air quality, decrease natural habitats in the area, and increase flooding in a vulnerable community which happens to be predominantly black.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Residents believe that the potential ecological damage was too much of a risk for some residents to stay idle; this is in addition to the potential increase of police violence.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The movement to stop “cop city” came about as the calls to defund the Atlanta Police Department grew in the wake of calls to defund police departments across the country.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There have been numerous organizations working to prevent construction from beginning through acts of moving into the forest, sabotaging equipment, and seeking legal action against the city and private companies who are working to supply equipment for the construction of the facility.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Many people outside of the community worked to stop “cop city” as well.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The forest that the Police Foundation seeks to build their facility on is a part of Native Muscogee land.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Tribe members traveled to the city to demand that the city end work and retreat from Muscogee land.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The movement to stop “cop city” became a group effort by individuals who wanted to see change in the justice system in Atlanta as well as individuals who wanted to protect the natural habitats as they seek justice for the nonhuman species of Atlanta’s forests.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Although a growing movement, there is pushback from the city and the Police Foundation who want the so called “cop city” to go forward and will do anything to get it done.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In defending the forest and trying to be heard and recognized by the city and the state government, protestors were met with harsh punishments; both legal and physical.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In protesting, a nonbinary environmental activist named Manuel Esteban Paez Terán, or Tortuguita, was killed by Georgia State Patrol on January 18 bringing to light the violent effects of police patrol and watch over protestors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As much as protestors are speaking up and out about the environmental destruction and negative effects of infrastructure, there are many laws and policies going into place that make it harder to exercise one’s free speech.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical Infrastructure (CI) Trespass Bills are being introduced across the country to allow for the detention and prosecution of protestors that get in the way of infrastructure construction.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] According to Jalbert et. al. and if these bills become law, they will allow for the use of drones, excessive force, facial recognition, and community surveillance tactics.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Further, Akbar, Love, and Donoghoe argue that these bills will disproportionality affect protestors of color.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This is seen by the death of Tortuguita and the mass arrest of Indigenous, black, and brown protesters.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Not only are there arrests and violent responses by law authorities, but there are also actions that officials are taking to make CI trespassing a felony as many cite the protest of critical infrastructure to be terroristic actions.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These laws stem from the growing systematic push to criminalize protestors from preventing the construction of new critical infrastructure; these laws are in response to country wide protests against pipeline construction.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These are protests that stem from the desire to protect the climate and to protect Indigenous lands.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Protests tend to work to stop/slow the construction of new pipelines and aim to speak out against the local, state, and federal governments who support, and in many cases, fund the addition of oil and gas pipelines.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Indigenous peoples argue that pipeline construction goes against tribal treaties as well as has the possibility to jeopardize the land through pollution.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The intertwining of alleged environmental and systemic oppression has pushed residents of areas due for pipeline construction to speak out and against the projects.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Due to oil and gas pipelines falling under the sector of energy, they are seen as critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Therefore, the US government aims to uphold and protect them.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] As a result, multiple states have deployed “Anti-Protest” laws to prevent the disruption of pipeline construction and any development of projects considered to be critical infrastructure and necessary for the advancement of the country.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These laws make it a felony to stall and prevent the construction and development of critical infrastructure projects within states that implement these various “anti-protest” laws.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Due to the growing political push to prevent protesters from interfering in infrastructure projects, Georgia has become a state that is slowly using “anti-protest” laws and measures to prevent people from protesting “cop city” and other critical infrastructure projects in the state.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Activists have been detained and charged with felonies as they protest “cop city”.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Critical Infrastructure Projects in the US has its supporters and its protestors and the response to these projects are made clear from all sides.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] PDD-63 mandated the formation of a national structure for critical infrastructure protection.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] To accomplish this one of the primary actions was to produce a National Infrastructure Assurance Plan, or NIAP, later renamed National Infrastructure Protection Plan or NIPP.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The different entities of the national CIP structure work together as a partnership between the government and the public sectors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Each department and agency of the federal government is responsible for protecting its portion of the government's critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In addition, there are grants made available through the Department of Homeland Security for municipal and private entities to use for CIP and security purposes.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These include grants for emergency management, water security training, rail, transit and port security, metropolitan medical response, LEA terrorism prevention programs and the Urban Areas Security Initiative.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] PDD-63 identified certain functions related to critical infrastructure protection that must be performed chiefly by the federal government.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] These are national defense, foreign affairs, intelligence, and law enforcement.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Each lead agency for these special functions appoints a senior official to serve as a functional coordinator for the federal government.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In 2008 a mobile PDA-based Vulnerability Assessment Security Survey Tool (VASST) was introduced to speed physical security assessment of critical infrastructure by law enforcement to meet compliance requirements of PDD-63.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The **National Infrastructure Protection Plan** (NIPP) is a document called for by Homeland Security Presidential Directive 7, which aims to unify Critical Infrastructure and Key Resource (CIKR) protection efforts across the country.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The latest version of the plan was produced in 2013 The NIPP's goals are to protect critical infrastructure and key resources and ensure resiliency.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] It is generally considered unwieldy and not an actual plan to be carried out in an emergency, but it is useful as a mechanism for developing coordination between government and the private sector.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The NIPP is based on the model laid out in the 1998 Presidential Decision Directive-63, which identified critical sectors of the economy and tasked relevant government agencies to work with them on sharing information and on strengthening responses to attack.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The NIPP is structured to create partnerships between Government Coordinating Councils (GCC) from the public sector and Sector Coordinating Councils (SCC) from the private sector for the eighteen sectors DHS has identified as critical.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] For each of the identified major sectors of the critical infrastructure, the federal government appointed a Sector Liaison Official from a designated Lead Agency.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] A private sector counterpart, a Sector Coordinator, was also identified.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Together, the two sector representatives, one federal government and one corporate, were responsible for developing a sector NIAP.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In addition, each department and agency of the federal government was responsible for developing its own CIP plan for protecting its portion of the federal government's critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The federal department and agency plans were assimilated with the sector NIAPs to create one comprehensive National Infrastructure Assurance Plan.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Additionally the national structure must ensure there is a national CIP program.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] This program includes responsibilities such as education and awareness, threat assessment and investigation, and research.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There have been public criticisms of the mechanisms and implementation of some security initiatives and grants, with claims they are being led by the same companies who can benefit, and that they are encouraging an unnecessary culture of fear.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Commentators note that these initiatives started directly after the collapse of the Cold War, raising the concern that this was simply a diversion of the military-industrial complex away from a funding area which was shrinking and into a richer previously civilian arena.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Grants have been distributed across the different states even though the perceived risk is not evenly spread, leading to accusations of pork barrel politics that directs money and jobs towards marginal voting areas.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The Urban Areas Security Initiative grant program has been particularly controversial, with the 2006 infrastructure list covering 77,000 assets, including a popcorn factory and a hot dog stand.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The 2007 criteria were reduced to 2,100 and now those facilities must make a much stronger case to become eligible for grants.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] While well-intentioned, some of the results have also been questioned regarding claims of poorly designed and intrusive security theater that distracts attention and money from more pressing issues or creates damaging side effects.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] An absence of comparative risk analysis and benefits tracking it has made it difficult to counter such allegations with authority.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In order to better understand this, and ultimately direct effort more productively, a Risk Management and Analysis Office was recently created in the National Protection and Programs directorate at the Department of Homeland Security.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Department of Defense is responsible for protecting its portion of the government's critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] But as part of the CIP program, DoD has responsibilities that traverse both the national and department-wide critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] PDD-63 identified the responsibilities DoD had for critical infrastructure protection.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] First, DoD had to identify its own critical assets and infrastructures and provide assurance through analysis, assessment, and remediation.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD was also responsible for identifying and monitoring the national and international infrastructure requirements of industry and other government agencies, all of which needed to be included in the protection planning.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD also addressed the assurance and protection of commercial assets and infrastructure services in DoD acquisitions.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Other DoD responsibilities for CIP included assessing the potential impact on military operations that would result from the loss or compromise of infrastructure service.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There were also requirements for monitoring DoD operations, detecting and responding to infrastructure incidents, and providing department indications and warnings as part of the national process.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] Ultimately, DoD was responsible for supporting national critical infrastructure protection.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] In response to the requirements identified in PDD-63, DoD categorized its own critical assets by sector, in a manner similar to the national CIP organization.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The DoD identified a slightly different list of infrastructure sectors for those areas that specifically required protection by DoD.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD's organizational structure for critical infrastructure protection reflects, complements, and effectively interacts with the national structure for CIP.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] There are ten defense critical infrastructure sectors that are protected by the DoD.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] The DoD CIP special function components interface with the equivalent national functional coordinators and coordinate all activities related to their function within DoD.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p01] DoD's special function components currently include seven areas of focus.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] As mandated by PDD-63, the DoD must protect its portion of the federal government's critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For DoD, this is the Defense Infrastructure or DI.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Protecting the Defense Infrastructure is a complex task involving ten defense sectors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] It was deemed that it was nearly impossible to protect every critical asset at every location, therefore the focus was directed on protecting the critical Defense Infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The critical Defense Infrastructure is the critical assets essential to providing mission assurance.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The six phases of the DoD CIP life cycle build on one another to create a framework for a comprehensive solution for infrastructure assurance.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The life cycle phases occur before, during, and after an event that may compromise or degrade the infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Effective management of the CIP life cycle ensures that protection activities can be coordinated and reconciled among all DoD sectors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In many ways, DoD CIP, is risk management at its most imperative.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Achieving success means obtaining mission assurance.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Missing the mark can mean mission failure as well as human and material losses.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For critical infrastructure protection, risk management requires leveraging resources to address the most critical infrastructure assets that are also the most vulnerable and that have the greatest threat exposure.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The most important part of the CIP lifecycle is Phase 1.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Because it is crucial to target the right assets for infrastructure protection, determining these assets is the first phase in the CIP life cycle.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] This phase, Analysis and Assessment, is the key and foundation of the seven lifecycle activities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Without a solid foundation, the remaining CIP life cycle phases may be flawed, resulting in a CIP plan that fails to protect the critical infrastructure and, therefore, mission assurance.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Phase 1 determines what assets are important, and identifies their vulnerabilities, and dependencies so that decision makers have the information they need to make effective risk management choices.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Defense Infrastructure, or DI, is organized into ten sectors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Each sector is composed of assets, such as systems, programs, people, equipment, or facilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Assets may be simple, such as one facility within one geographic location, or complex, involving geographically dispersed links and nodes.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Analysis and Assessment is made up of five steps that include activities that span and encompass the ten DI sectors and their assets.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] On August 24, 2001, the Director of the Joint Staff requested USPACOM to serve as the lead support Combatant Command for creating a CIP first-ever theater CIP Plan – known as the “CIP Appendix 16 Plan”.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The following is how USPACOM approached the task.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] To accomplish these steps, USPACOM adopted a methodology that focuses its CIP efforts on Tier 1 assets.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Tier 1 assets are assets that could cause mission failure if they are compromised or damaged.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The methodology UAPACOM adopted and modified is Mission Area Analysis, or MAA.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The MAA links combatant command missions to infrastructure assets that are critical to a given Operations Plan, or OPLAN, Contingency Plan, or CONPLAN, or Crisis Action Plan.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Typically, the MAA process determines the assessment site priorities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] USPACOM modified the process and selected the CIP assessment sites and installations prior to conducting the MAA.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] USPACOM uses the MAA data it gathers to scope and focus its efforts on truly mission-critical assets to answer the next question in its process, Is it vulnerable?
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The first step in answering this question is to complete an installation analysis.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The next step is to complete a commercial infrastructure analysis.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] USPACOM relied upon two different DoD organizations for CIP assessments: Balanced Survivability Assessments, or BSAs, and Mission Assurance Assessments.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The BSA is a two-week mission-focused assessment at a military installation or designated site.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] A Mission Assurance Assessment is unique because it uses an area assessment approach to focus on both commercial and military asset vulnerabilities and dependencies.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The final step to determine vulnerabilities is to integrate the two analyses and assessments.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] With its critical assets and their vulnerabilities identified, USPACOM is ready to perform risk management activities to decide what can be done to protect the mission-critical assets.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Booz Allen Hamilton developed this process at PACOM.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The first phase of the CIP life cycle, Analysis and Assessment, identified the critical assets of DoD sector infrastructures and the vulnerabilities or weaknesses of those critical assets.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The second phase is the Remediation phase.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In the Remediation phase, the known weaknesses and vulnerabilities are addressed.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation actions are deliberate, precautionary measures designed to fix known virtual and physical vulnerabilities before an event occurs.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The purpose of remediation is to improve the reliability, availability, and survivability of critical assets and infrastructures.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation actions apply to any type of vulnerability, regardless of its cause.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] They apply to acts of nature, technology failures, or deliberate malicious actions.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The cost of each remediation action depends on the nature of the vulnerability it addresses.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Defense Infrastructure Sector Assurance Plan that each infrastructure sector must develop, establishes the priorities and resources for remediation.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation requirements are determined by multiple factors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These are analysis and assessment, input from military planners and other DoD sectors, the National Infrastructure Assurance Plan and other plans, reports, and information on national infrastructure vulnerabilities and remediation, as well as intelligence estimates and assessments of threats.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation requirements are also gathered through lessons learned from Defense Infrastructure sector monitoring and reporting and infrastructure protection operations and exercises.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The CIP program tracks the status of remediation activities for critical assets.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Remediation activities to protect the critical Defense Infrastructure cross multiple Department components.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The need to monitor activities and warn of potential threats to the United States is not new.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] From conventional assaults to potential nuclear attacks, the military has been at the forefront of monitoring and warning of potential dangers since the founding of the country.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Protecting the security and well-being of the United States, including the critical Defense Infrastructure, has now entered a new era.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] It has been deemed essential to have a coordinated ability to identify and warn of potential or actual incidents among critical infrastructure domains.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The ability to detect and warn of infrastructure events is the third phase of the critical infrastructure protection life cycle, the Indications and Warnings phase.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Historically, DoD event indications have focused and relied on intelligence information about foreign developments.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These event indications have been expanded to include all potential infrastructure disruption or degradation, regardless of its cause.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] This fusion of traditional intelligence information with sector-specific information has been determined to be essential for meaningful CIP indications.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] If an indication is detected, a warning notifying the appropriate asset owners of a possible or occurring event or hazard can be issued.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The sector's assurance plan determines what conditions and actions are monitored and reported for each Defense Infrastructure Sector.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Each sector must develop a written Defense Sector Assurance Plan that includes a compendium of sector incidents for monitoring and reporting.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] DoD critical asset owners, installations, and sector CIAOs determine the DoD and sector-defined incidents.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The National Infrastructure Protection Center (NIPC) is the primary national warning center for significant infrastructure attacks.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Critical asset owners, DoD installations, and Sector CIAOs monitor the infrastructure daily.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Indications of an infrastructure incident are reported to the National Military Command Center, or NMCC.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] If indications are on a computer network, they are also reported to the Joint Task Force Computer Network Operations (JTF-CNO).
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The NMCC and JTF-CNO assess the indications and pass them to the NIPC and appropriate DoD organizations.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When the NIPC determines that an infrastructure event is likely to occur, is planned, or is under way, it issues a national warning.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For DoD, the NIPC passes its warnings and alerts to the NMCC and JTF-CNO.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These warnings and alerts are then passed to the DoD components.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The warning may include guidance regarding additional protection measures DoD should take.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Phase 1 of the CIP life cycle provided a layer of protection by identifying and assessing critical assets and their vulnerabilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Phase 2 provided another layer of protection by remediating or improving the identified deficiencies and weaknesses of an asset.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Even with these protections and precautions, an infrastructure incident was still possible.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When it does the Indications and Warnings phase goes into effect.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The Mitigation phase (Phase 4), is made up of preplanned coordinated actions in response to infrastructure warnings or incidents.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Mitigation actions are taken before or during an infrastructure event.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These actions are designed to minimize the operational impact of the loss of a critical asset, facilitate incident response, and quickly restore the infrastructure service.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] A primary purpose of the Mitigation phase is to minimize the operational impact on other critical Defense Infrastructures and assets when a critical asset is lost or damaged.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] As an example, if there is a U.S. installation, Site A, located in a host nation.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Site A is a tier 1 asset, meaning that if it fails, the Combatant Commands mission fails.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Site A has mutual Global Information Grid Command Control (GIG/C2), information interdependencies with Sites B and C.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In addition, other Defense Infrastructure sectors rely on Site A for mission capabilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In this scenario, what could be the impact if the supply line to the commercial power plant that provides the installation's primary power is accidentally severed.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Because of all the interdependencies, losing this asset is more than the loss of just one site.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] It means the loss of other sector capabilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] A possible mitigation action might be for Site A to go on backup power.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] An alternate action could be to pass complete control of Site A's functionality to another site, where redundancy has been previously arranged.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These actions would limit the impact of this incident on the other sites and related sectors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] In addition to lessening the operational impact of a critical infrastructure event, the Mitigation phase of the CIP life cycle supports and complements two other life cycle phases.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Mitigation actions aid in the emergency, investigation, and management activities of Phase 5, Incident Response.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] They also facilitate the reconstitution activities of Phase 6.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When there is a warning, emergency, or infrastructure incident, the critical asset owners, installations, and Sector CIAOs initiate mitigation actions to sustain service to the DoD.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] They also provide mitigation status information to the NMCC and JTF-CNO.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The NMCC monitors for consequences from an event within one Defense Infrastructure sector that are significant enough to affect other sectors.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For events that cross two or more sectors, the NMCC advises on the prioritization and coordination of mitigation actions.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When event threats or consequences continue to escalate, the NMCC directs mitigation actions by sector to ensure a coordinated response across the DoD.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The NMCC and the JTF-CNO keep the National Infrastructure Protection Center, or NIPC, apprised of any significant mitigation activities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When an event affects the Defense Infrastructure, the Incident Response phase begins.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Incident Response is the fifth phase of the CIP life cycle.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] The purpose of the Incident Response phase is to eliminate the cause or source of an infrastructure event.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] For example, during the 9/11 attacks on the World Trade Center and Pentagon, all non-military airplanes were grounded over the United States to prevent further incidents.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Response activities included emergency measures, not from the asset owners or operators, but from dedicated third parties such as law enforcement, medical rescue, fire rescue, hazardous material or explosives handling, and investigative agencies.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Response to Defense Infrastructure incidents can take one of two paths depending on whether or not the event affects a DoD computer network.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When incidents compromise a DoD computer network, the Joint Task Force-Computer Network Operations (JTF-CNO) directs the response activities.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] These activities are designed to stop the computer network attack, contain and mitigate damage to a DoD information network and then restore minimum required functionality.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] JTF-CNO also requests and coordinates any support or assistance from other Federal agencies and civilian organizations during incidents affecting a DoD network.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] When incidents impact any other DoD owned assets, installation commanders and critical asset owners follow traditional channels and procedures to coordinate responses.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] This includes notifying affected Sector Chief Infrastructure Assurance Officers, or CIAOs, in the initial notice and status reporting.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Although third parties play a major role in the response to Defense Infrastructure events, DoD CIP personnel also have responsibilities to fulfill.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] After the source or cause of an infrastructure event is eliminated or contained, the infrastructure and its capabilities must be restored.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Reconstitution is the last phase of the critical infrastructure protection.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] Reconstitution is probably the most challenging and least developed process of the life cycle.
[src:industrial-control-security/critical-infrastructure-protection-p02] DoD critical asset owners have the major responsibility for reconstitution.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] An **industrial control system** (**ICS**) is an electronic control system and associated instrumentation used for industrial process control.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems can range in size from a few modular panel-mounted controllers to large interconnected and interactive distributed control systems (DCSs) with many thousands of field connections.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Control systems receive data from remote sensors measuring process variables (PVs), compare the collected data with desired setpoints (SPs), and derive command functions that are used to control a process through the final control elements (FCEs), such as control valves.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Larger systems are usually implemented by supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems, or DCSs, and programmable logic controllers (PLCs), though SCADA and PLC systems are scalable down to small systems with few control loops.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Such systems are extensively used in industries such as chemical processing, pulp and paper manufacture, power generation, oil and gas processing, and telecommunications.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The simplest control systems are based around small discrete controllers with a single control loop each.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] These are usually panel mounted, which allows direct viewing of the front panel and provides a means of manual intervention by the operator, either to manually control the process or to change control setpoints.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Originally, these would be pneumatic controllers, a few of which are still in use, but nearly all are now electronic.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Quite complex systems can be created with networks of these controllers communicating using industry-standard protocols.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Networking allows the use of local or remote SCADA operator interfaces and enables the cascading and interlocking of controllers.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] However, as the number of control loops increases for a system design, there is a point where the use of a programmable logic controller (PLC) or distributed control system (DCS) is more manageable or cost-effective.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] A distributed control system (DCS) is a digital process control system (PCS) for a process or plant, wherein controller functions and field connection modules are distributed throughout the system.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] As the number of control loops grows, DCS becomes more cost effective than discrete controllers.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, a DCS provides supervisory viewing and management over large industrial processes.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] In a DCS, a hierarchy of controllers is connected by communication networks, allowing centralized control rooms and local on-plant monitoring and control.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS enables easy configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other computer systems such as production control.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] It also enables more sophisticated alarm handling, introduces automatic event logging, removes the need for physical records such as chart recorders and allows the control equipment to be networked and thereby located locally to the equipment being controlled to reduce cabling.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] A DCS typically uses custom-designed processors as controllers and uses either proprietary interconnections or standard protocols for communication.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Input and output modules form the peripheral components of the system.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be performed by the output modules.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The input modules receive information from sensing instruments in the process (or field) and the output modules transmit instructions to the final control elements, such as control valves.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can either be continuously changing analog signals, e.g., current loop or 2-state signals that switch either *on* or *off*, such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Distributed control systems can normally also support Foundation Fieldbus, PROFIBUS, HART, Modbus and other digital communication buses that carry not only input and output signals but also advanced messages such as error diagnostics and status signals.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) is a control system architecture that uses computers, networked data communications and graphical user interfaces for high-level process supervisory management.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA supervisory computer system.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] However, the real-time control logic or controller calculations are performed by networked modules which connect to other peripheral devices such as programmable logic controllers and discrete PID controllers which interface to the process plant or machinery.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA concept was developed as a universal means of remote access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers, allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become very similar to distributed control systems in function, but using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] They can control large-scale processes that can include multiple sites and work over large distances.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] This is a commonly used architecture industrial control systems, however there are concerns about SCADA systems being vulnerable to cyberwarfare or cyberterrorism attacks.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA software operates on a supervisory level as control actions are performed automatically by RTUs or PLCs.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA control functions are usually restricted to basic overriding or supervisory level intervention.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] A feedback control loop is directly controlled by the RTU or PLC, but the SCADA software monitors the overall performance of the loop.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] For example, a PLC may control the flow of cooling water through part of an industrial process to a set point level, but the SCADA system software will allow operators to change the set points for the flow.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The SCADA also enables alarm conditions, such as loss of flow or high temperature, to be displayed and recorded.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O) in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Initially, control was from panels local to the process plant.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] However, this required personnel to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Often, the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were individually transmitted back to the plant in the form of pneumatic or electrical signals.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Effectively, this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of reduced manpower requirements and a consolidated overview of the process.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, so system changes required reconfiguration of signals by re-piping or re-wiring.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] It also required continual operator movement within a large control room in order to monitor the whole process.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors, high-speed electronic signalling networks and electronic graphic displays, it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] These could be distributed around the plant and would communicate with the graphic displays in the control room.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The concept of *distributed control* was realised.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The introduction of distributed control allowed flexible interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] For large control systems, the general commercial name *distributed control system* (DCS) was coined to refer to proprietary modular systems from many manufacturers that integrated high-speed networking and a full suite of displays and control racks.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] While the DCS was tailored to meet the needs of large continuous industrial processes, in industries where combinatorial and sequential logic was the primary requirement, the PLC evolved out of a need to replace racks of relays and timers used for event-driven control.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The old controls were difficult to reconfigure and debug, and PLC control enabled networking of signals to a central control area with electronic displays.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] PLCs were first developed for the automotive industry on vehicle production lines, where sequential logic was becoming very complex.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] It was soon adopted in a large number of other event-driven applications as varied as printing presses and water treatment plants.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA's history is rooted in distribution applications, such as power, natural gas, and water pipelines, where there is a need to gather remote data through potentially unreliable or intermittent low-bandwidth and high-latency links.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA systems use open-loop control with sites that are widely separated geographically.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] A SCADA system uses remote terminal units (RTUs) to send supervisory data back to a control centre.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Most RTU systems always had some capacity to handle local control while the master station is not available.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] However, over the years, RTU systems have grown more and more capable of handling local control.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The boundaries between DCS and SCADA/PLC systems are blurring as time goes on.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The technical limits that drove the designs of these various systems are no longer as much of an issue.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Many PLC platforms can now perform quite well as a small DCS, using remote I/O and are sufficiently reliable that some SCADA systems actually manage closed-loop control over long distances.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] With the increasing speed of today's processors, many DCS products have a full line of PLC-like subsystems that weren't offered when they were initially developed.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] In 1993, with the release of IEC-1131, later to become IEC-61131-3, the industry moved towards increased code standardization with reusable, hardware-independent control software.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] For the first time, object-oriented programming (OOP) became possible within industrial control systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] This led to the development of both programmable automation controllers (PAC) and industrial PCs (IPC).
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] These are platforms programmed in the five standardized IEC languages: ladder logic, structured text, function block, instruction list and sequential function chart.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] They can also be programmed in modern high-level languages such as C or C++.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Additionally, they accept models developed in analytical tools such as MATLAB and Simulink.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Unlike traditional PLCs, which use proprietary operating systems, IPCs utilize Windows IoT.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] IPCs have the advantage of powerful multi-core processors with much lower hardware costs than traditional PLCs and fit well into multiple form factors such as DIN rail mount, combined with a touch-screen as a panel PC, or as an embedded PC.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] New hardware platforms and technology have contributed significantly to the evolution of DCS and SCADA systems, further blurring the boundaries and changing definitions.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] SCADA and PLCs are vulnerable to cyber attack.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] Government Joint Capability Technology Demonstration (JCTD) known as MOSAICS (More Situational Awareness for Industrial Control Systems) is the initial demonstration of cybersecurity defensive capability for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] MOSAICS addresses the Department of Defense (DOD) operational need for cyber defense capabilities to defend critical infrastructure control systems from cyber attack, such as power, water and wastewater, and safety controls, affect the physical environment.
[src:industrial-control-security/industrial-control-system] The MOSAICS JCTD prototype will be shared with commercial industry through Industry Days for further research and development, an approach intended to lead to an innovative, game-changing capabilities for cybersecurity for critical infrastructure control systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] The built environment, whether commercial or domestic, is increasingly controlled and monitored via Internet of Things (IoT) and Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) devices.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] In this application space, these IoT devices are both interconnected via converged technology edge IoT platforms and or via "cloud" based applications.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Embedded Systems are also included in the sphere of operational technology (e.g. smart instrumentation), along with a large subset of scientific data acquisition, control, and computing devices.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Systems that process operational data (including electronic, telecommunications, computer systems and technical components) are included under the term operational technology.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] OT systems can be required to control valves, engines, conveyors and other machines to regulate various process values, such as temperature, pressure, flow, and to monitor them to prevent hazardous conditions.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] OT systems use various technologies for hardware design and communications protocols, that are unknown in IT.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Common problems include supporting legacy systems & devices and numerous vendor architectures and standards.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Since OT systems often supervise industrial processes, most of the time availability must be sustained.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] This often means that real time (or near-real time) processing is required, with high rates of reliability and availability.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] This kind of environment may also be referred to as industrial information technology (IIT).
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Historical OT networks utilized proprietary protocols optimized for the required functions, some of which have become adopted as 'standard' industrial communications protocols (e.g.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] DNP3, Modbus, Profibus, LonWorks, DALI, BACnet, KNX, EnOcean and OPC-UA).
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] More recently IT-standard network protocols are being implemented in OT devices and systems to reduce complexity and increase compatibility with more traditional IT hardware (e.g.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] TCP/IP); this however has had a demonstrable reduction in security for OT systems, which in the past have relied on air gaps and the inability to run PC-based malware (see Stuxnet for a well-known example of this change).
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] The term operational technology as applied to industrial control systems was first published in a research paper from Gartner in May 2006 (Steenstrup, Sumic, Spiers, Williams) and presented publicly in September 2006 at the Gartner Energy and Utilities IT Summit.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Initially the term was applied to power utility control systems, but over time was adopted by other industrial sectors and used in combination with IoT.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] A principal driver of the adoption of the term was that the nature of operational technology platforms had evolved from bespoke proprietary systems to complex software portfolios that rely on IT infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] This change was termed IT OT convergence.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] The concept of aligning and integrating the IT and OT systems of industrial companies gained importance as companies realized that physical assets and infrastructure was both managed by OT systems but also generated data for the IT systems running the business.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Industrial technology companies such as GE, Hitachi, Honeywell, Siemens, ABB and Rockwell are the main providers of OT platforms and systems either embedded in equipment or added to them for control, management and monitoring.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] These industrial technology companies have needed to evolve into software companies rather than being strictly machine providers.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Security of operational technology systems has historically relied almost entirely on the standalone nature of OT installations, security by obscurity.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] At least since 2005 OT systems have become linked to IT systems with the corporate goal of widening an organization's ability to monitor and adjust its OT systems, which has introduced massive challenges in securing them.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Approaches known from regular IT are usually replaced or redesigned to align with the OT environment.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] The intersection of operational technology and standard networking infrastructure exposes industrial processes to several distinct categories of risk.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Mitigation of these integrated risks typically involves the adoption of multi-layered security frameworks, continuous anomaly monitoring, and adherence to established institutional standards such as the ISA/IEC 62443 series.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Operational technology is widely used in refineries, power plants, nuclear plants, etc. and as such has become a common, crucial element of critical infrastructure systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] Depending on the country, critical infrastructure operators may face increasing legal obligations with regard to the implementation of OT systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] For several decades, hundreds of thousands of buildings have been upgraded with IoT building management, automation and smart lighting control solutions, but many of these solutions lack the proper security measures.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] This has recently led to bad actors exploiting such solutions' vulnerabilities with ransomware attacks causing system lock outs, operational failures exposing businesses operating in such buildings to the immense risks to health and safety, operations, brand reputation and financial damage.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] There is a strong focus put on subjects like IT/OT cooperation or IT/OT alignment in the modern industrial setting.
[src:industrial-control-security/operational-technology] The Stuxnet malware is one example of this, highlighting the potential for disaster should a safety system become infected with malware (whether targeted at that system or accidentally infected).
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:industrial-control-security/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet specifically targets programmable logic controllers (PLCs), which allow the automation of electromechanical processes such as those used to control machinery and industrial processes including gas centrifuges for separating nuclear material.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Exploiting four zero-day flaws in the systems, Stuxnet functions by targeting machines using the Microsoft Windows operating system and networks, then seeking out Siemens Step7 software.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet reportedly compromised Iranian PLCs, collecting information on industrial systems and causing the fast-spinning centrifuges to tear themselves apart.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet's design and architecture are not domain-specific and it could be tailored as a platform for attacking modern SCADA and PLC systems (e.g., in factory assembly lines or power plants), most of which are in Europe, Japan and the United States.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet reportedly destroyed almost one-fifth of Iran's nuclear centrifuges.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Targeting industrial control systems, the worm infected over 200,000 computers and caused 1,000 machines to physically degrade.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet has three modules: a worm that executes all routines related to the main payload of the attack, a link file that automatically executes the propagated copies of the worm and a rootkit component responsible for hiding all malicious files and processes to prevent detection of Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] It is typically introduced to the target environment via an infected USB flash drive, thus crossing any air gap.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The worm then propagates across the network, scanning for Siemens Step7 software on computers controlling a PLC.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In the absence of either criterion, Stuxnet becomes dormant inside the computer.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] If both the conditions are fulfilled, Stuxnet introduces the infected rootkit onto the PLC and Step7 software, modifying the code and giving unexpected commands to the PLC while returning a loop of normal operation system values back to the users.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet, discovered by Sergey Ulasen from a Belarusian antivirus company VirusBlokAda, initially spread via Microsoft Windows, and targeted Siemens industrial control systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The worm initially spreads indiscriminately, but includes a highly specialized malware payload that is designed to target only Siemens supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems that are configured to control and monitor specific industrial processes.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet infects PLCs by subverting the Step-7 software application that is used to reprogram these devices.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Different variants of Stuxnet targeted five Iranian organizations, with the probable target widely suspected to be uranium enrichment infrastructure in Iran; Symantec noted in August 2010 that 60 percent of the infected computers worldwide were in Iran.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Siemens stated that the worm caused no damage to its customers, but the Iran nuclear program, which uses embargoed Siemens equipment procured secretly, was damaged by Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky Lab concluded that the sophisticated attack could only have been conducted "with nation-state support".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to *The Daily Telegraph*, a showreel that was played at a retirement party for the head of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF), Gabi Ashkenazi, included references to Stuxnet as one of his operational successes as the IDF chief of staff.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 1 June 2012, an article in *The New York Times* reported that Stuxnet was part of a US and Israeli intelligence operation named *Operation Olympic Games*, devised by the NSA under President George W.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Bush and executed under President Barack Obama.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 24 July 2012, an article by Chris Matyszczyk from CNET reported that the Atomic Energy Organization of Iran e-mailed F-Secure's chief research officer Mikko Hyppönen to report a new instance of malware.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 25 December 2012, an Iranian semi-official news agency announced there was a cyberattack by Stuxnet, this time on the industries in the southern area of the country.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The malware targeted a power plant and some other industries in Hormozgan province in 2012.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to Eugene Kaspersky, the worm also infected a nuclear power plant in Russia.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky noted, however, that since the power plant is not connected to the public Internet, the system should remain safe.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The worm was first identified by the security company VirusBlokAda in mid-June 2010.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Journalist Brian Krebs's blog post on 15 July 2010 was the first widely read report on the worm.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The original name given by VirusBlokAda was "Rootkit.Tmphider;" Symantec, however, called it "W32.Temphid", later changing it to "W32.Stuxnet".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Its current name is derived from a combination of keywords found in the software (".stub" and "mrxnet.sys").
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The timing of the discovery has been attributed to the virus accidentally spreading beyond its intended target due to a programming error introduced in an update.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] This may have caused the worm to spread to an engineer's computer connected to the centrifuges, further propagating when the engineer later connected to the internet at home.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky Lab experts initially estimated that Stuxnet began spreading around March or April 2010, but the first variant of the worm appeared in June 2009.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 15 July 2010, the day the worm's existence became widely known, a distributed denial-of-service attack targeted the servers of two leading mailing lists on industrial-systems security.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] This attack, from an unknown source but possibly related to Stuxnet, disabled one of the lists, interrupting a key information source for power plants and factories.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Separately, researchers at Symantec uncovered a version of the Stuxnet computer virus that was used to attack Iran's nuclear program in November 2007, with evidence indicating it was under development as early as 2005, when Iran was still setting up its uranium enrichment facility.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The second variant, with substantial improvements, appeared in March 2010, reportedly due to concerns that Stuxnet was not spreading fast enough.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] A third variant, with minor improvements, followed in April 2010.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The worm contains a component with a build timestamp from 3 February 2010.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 25 November 2010, Sky News in the United Kingdom reported receiving information from an anonymous source at an unidentified IT security organization claiming that Stuxnet, or a variation of the worm, had been traded on the black market.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2015, Kaspersky Lab reported that the Equation Group had used two of the same zero-day attacks prior to their use in Stuxnet, in another malware called fanny.bmp.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Kaspersky Lab noted that "the similar type of usage of both exploits together in different computer worms, at around the same time, indicates that the Equation Group and the Stuxnet developers are either the same or working closely together".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2019, *Chronicle* researchers Juan Andres Guerrero-Saade and Silas Cutler presented findings indicating that at least four distinct threat actor malware platforms collaborated in developing the different versions of Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The collaboration was referred to as 'GOSSIP GIRL', a name derived from a threat group mentioned in classified CSE slides that included Flame.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] GOSSIP GIRL is described as a cooperative umbrella encompassing the Equation Group, Flame, Duqu, and Flowershop (also known as 'Cheshire Cat').
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2020, researcher Facundo Muñoz presented findings suggesting that Equation Group may have collaborated with Stuxnet developers in 2009 by providing at least one zero-day exploit, and one exploit from 2008 that was actively used by the Conficker computer worm and Chinese hackers.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2017, a group of hackers known as The Shadow Brokers leaked a collection of tools attributed to Equation Group, including new versions of both exploits compiled in 2010.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Analysis of the leaked data indicated significant code overlaps, as both Stuxnet's exploits and Equation Group's exploits were developed using a set of libraries called the "Exploit Development Framework", also leaked by The Shadow Brokers.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Iran was reported to have fortified its cyberwar abilities following the Stuxnet attack, and has been suspected of retaliatory attacks.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] These include attacks against United States banks in the Operation Ababil campaign of 2012-2013, the 2012 Shamoon attack against oil giant Saudi Aramco, and the 2014 strike against Las Vegas Sands Corporation.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Unlike most malware, Stuxnet does little harm to computers and networks that do not meet specific configuration requirements; "The attackers took great care to make sure that only their designated targets were hit ...
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] It was a marksman's job." While the worm is promiscuous, it makes itself inert if Siemens software is not found on infected computers, and contains safeguards to prevent each infected computer from spreading the worm to more than three others, and to erase itself on 24 June 2012.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] For its targets, Stuxnet contains, among other things, code for a man-in-the-middle attack that fakes industrial process control sensor signals so an infected system does not shut down due to detected abnormal behavior.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet attacked Windows systems using an unprecedented four zero-day attacks (plus the CPLINK vulnerability and a vulnerability used by the Conficker worm).
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] It is initially spread using infected removable drives such as USB flash drives, which contain Windows shortcut files to initiate executable code.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The worm then uses other exploits and techniques such as peer-to-peer remote procedure call (RPC) to infect and update other computers inside private networks that are not directly connected to the Internet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The number of zero-day exploits used is unusual, as they are highly valued and malware creators do not typically make use of (and thus simultaneously make visible) four different zero-day exploits in the same worm.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Amongst these exploits were remote code execution on a computer with Printer Sharing enabled, and the LNK/PIF vulnerability, in which file execution is accomplished when an icon is viewed in Windows Explorer, negating the need for user interaction.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet is unusually large at half a megabyte in size, and written in several different programming languages (including C and C++) which is also irregular for malware.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The Windows component of the malware is promiscuous in that it spreads relatively quickly and indiscriminately.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The driver signing helped it install kernel mode rootkit drivers successfully without users being notified, and thus it remained undetected for a relatively long period of time.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Both compromised certificates have been revoked by Verisign.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Two websites in Denmark and Malaysia were configured as command and control servers for the malware, allowing it to be updated, and for industrial espionage to be conducted by uploading information.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Both of these domain names have subsequently been redirected by their DNS service provider to Dynadot as part of a global effort to disable the malware.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to researcher Ralph Langner, once installed on a Windows system, Stuxnet infects project files belonging to Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 SCADA control software (Step 7), and subverts a key communication library of WinCC called `s7otbxdx.dll`.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Doing so intercepts communications between the WinCC software running under Windows and the target Siemens PLC devices, when the two are connected via a data cable.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The malware is able to modify the code on PLC devices unnoticed, and subsequently to mask its presence from WinCC if the control software attempts to read an infected block of memory from the PLC system.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The malware also used a zero-day exploit in the WinCC/SCADA database software in the form of a hard-coded database password.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet's payload targets only those SCADA configurations that meet criteria that it is programmed to identify.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet requires specific subordinate system to be attached to the targeted Siemens S7-300 controller system: variable-frequency drives (frequency converter drives) and its associated modules.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] It only attacks those PLC systems with variable-frequency drives from two specific vendors: Vacon based in Finland and Fararo Paya based in Iran.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Furthermore, it monitors the frequency of the attached motors, and only attacks systems that spin between 807 Hz and 1,210 Hz.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] This is a much higher frequency than motors typically operate at in most industrial applications, with the notable exception of gas centrifuges.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet installs malware into memory block DB890 of the PLC that monitors the Profibus messaging bus of the system.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] When certain criteria are met, it periodically modifies the frequency to 1,410 Hz and then to 2 Hz and then to 1,064 Hz, and thus affects the operation of the connected motors by changing their rotational speed.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] It also installs a rootkit – the first such documented case on this platform – that hides the malware on the system and masks the changes in rotational speed from monitoring systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Siemens has released a detection and removal tool for Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Siemens recommends contacting customer support if an infection is detected and advises installing Microsoft updates for security vulnerabilities and prohibiting the use of third-party USB flash drives.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Siemens also advises immediately upgrading password access codes.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The worm's ability to reprogram external PLCs may complicate the removal procedure.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Symantec's Liam O'Murchu warns that fixing Windows systems may not fully solve the infection; a thorough audit of PLCs may be necessary.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Despite speculation that incorrect removal of the worm could cause damage, Siemens reports that in the first four months since discovery, the malware was successfully removed from the systems of 22 customers without any adverse effects.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Prevention of control system security incidents, such as from viral infections like Stuxnet, is a topic that is being addressed in both the public and the private sector.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The US Department of Homeland Security National Cyber Security Division (NCSD) operates the Control System Security Program (CSSP).
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The program operates a specialized computer emergency response team called the Industrial Control Systems Cyber Emergency Response Team (ICS-CERT), conducts a biannual conference (ICSJWG), provides training, publishes recommended practices, and provides a self-assessment tool.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] As part of a Department of Homeland Security plan to improve American computer security, in 2008 it and the Idaho National Laboratory (INL) worked with Siemens to identify security holes in the company's widely used Process Control System 7 (PCS 7) and its software Step 7.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In July 2008, INL and Siemens publicly announced flaws in the control system at a Chicago conference; Stuxnet exploited these holes in 2009.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Several industry organizations and professional societies have published standards and best practice guidelines providing direction and guidance for control system end-users on how to establish a control system security management program.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The basic premise that all of these documents share is that prevention requires a multi-layered approach, often termed *defense in depth*.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The layers include policies and procedures, awareness and training, network segmentation, access control measures, physical security measures, system hardening, e.g., patch management, and system monitoring, anti-virus and intrusion prevention system (IPS).
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The standards and best practices also all recommend starting with a risk analysis and a control system security assessment.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Stuxnet may be the largest and costliest development effort in malware history.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Developing its abilities would have required a team of capable programmers, in-depth knowledge of industrial processes, and an interest in attacking industrial infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Eric Byres, who has years of experience maintaining and troubleshooting Siemens systems, told *Wired* that writing the code would have taken many man-months, if not man-years.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Symantec estimates that the group developing Stuxnet would have consisted of between five and thirty people, and would have taken six months to prepare.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] *The Guardian*, the BBC and *The New York Times* all claimed that (unnamed) experts studying Stuxnet believe the complexity of the code indicates that only a nation-state would have the abilities to produce it.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The self-destruct and other safeguards within the code implied that a Western government was responsible, or at least is responsible for its development.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] However, software security expert Bruce Schneier initially condemned the 2010 news coverage of Stuxnet as hype, stating that it was almost entirely based on speculation.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] But after subsequent research, Schneier stated in 2012 that "we can now conclusively link Stuxnet to the centrifuge structure at the Natanz nuclear enrichment lab in Iran".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In late December 2008, Dutch engineer Erik van Sabben travelled to Iran, allegedly to infiltrate the Natanz nuclear facility on behalf of Dutch intelligence and install equipment infected with Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] He died two weeks after the Stuxnet attack at age 36 in an apparent single-vehicle motorcycle accident in Dubai.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Ralph Langner, the researcher who identified that Stuxnet infected PLCs, first speculated publicly in September 2010 that the malware was of Israeli origin, and that it targeted Iranian nuclear facilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] However Langner more recently, at a TED conference, recorded in February 2011, stated that "My opinion is that the Mossad is involved, but that the leading force is not Israel.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Langner called the malware "a one-shot weapon" and said that the intended target was probably hit, although he admitted this was speculation.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Another German researcher and spokesman of the German-based Chaos Computer Club, Frank Rieger, was the first to speculate that Natanz was the target.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 23 November 2010 it was announced that uranium enrichment at Natanz had ceased several times because of a series of major technical problems.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] A "serious nuclear accident" (supposedly the shutdown of some of its centrifuges) occurred at the site in the first half of 2009, which is speculated to have forced Gholam Reza Aghazadeh, the head of the Atomic Energy Organization of Iran (AEOI), to resign.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Statistics published by the Federation of American Scientists (FAS) show that the number of enrichment centrifuges operational in Iran mysteriously declined from about 4,700 to about 3,900 beginning around the time the nuclear incident WikiLeaks mentioned would have occurred.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) suggests, in a report published in December 2010, that Stuxnet is a reasonable explanation for the apparent damage at Natanz, and may have destroyed up to 1,000 centrifuges (10 percent) sometime between November 2009 and late January 2010.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) report further notes that Iranian authorities have attempted to conceal the breakdown by installing new centrifuges on a large scale.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The worm worked by first causing an infected Iranian IR-1 centrifuge to increase from its normal operating speed of 1,064 hertz to 1,410 hertz for 15 minutes before returning to its normal frequency.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Twenty-seven days later, the worm went back into action, slowing the infected centrifuges down to a few hundred hertz for a full 50 minutes.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The stresses from the excessive, then slower, speeds caused the aluminium centrifugal tubes to expand, often forcing parts of the centrifuges into sufficient contact with each other to destroy the machine.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to *The Washington Post*, International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) cameras installed in the Natanz facility recorded the sudden dismantling and removal of approximately 900–1,000 centrifuges during the time the Stuxnet worm was reportedly active at the plant.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Iranian technicians, however, were able to quickly replace the centrifuges and the report concluded that uranium enrichment was likely only briefly disrupted.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The Associated Press reported that the semi-official Iranian Students News Agency released a statement on 24 September 2010 stating that experts from the Atomic Energy Organization of Iran met in the previous week to discuss how Stuxnet could be removed from their systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to analysts, such as David Albright, Western intelligence agencies had been attempting to sabotage the Iranian nuclear program for some time.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The Director of Information Technology Council at the Iranian Ministry of Industries and Mines, Mahmud Liaii, has said that: "An electronic war has been launched against Iran ...
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In response to the infection, Iran assembled a team to combat it.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] With more than 30,000 IP addresses affected in Iran, an official said that the infection was fast spreading in Iran and the problem had been compounded by the ability of Stuxnet to mutate.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Iran had set up its own systems to clean up infections and had advised against using the Siemens SCADA antivirus since it is suspected that the antivirus contains embedded code which updates Stuxnet instead of removing it.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to Hamid Alipour, deputy head of Iran's government Information Technology Company, "The attack is still ongoing and new versions of this virus are spreading." He reported that his company had begun the cleanup process at Iran's "sensitive centres and organizations".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] "We had anticipated that we could root out the virus within one to two months, but the virus is not stable, and since we started the cleanup process three new versions of it have been spreading", he told the Islamic Republic News Agency on 27 September 2010.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 29 November 2010, Iranian president Mahmoud Ahmadinejad stated for the first time that a computer virus had caused problems with the controller handling the centrifuges at its Natanz facilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On the same day two Iranian nuclear scientists were targeted in separate, but nearly simultaneous car bomb attacks near Shahid Beheshti University in Tehran.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Majid Shahriari, a quantum physicist, was killed.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Fereydoon Abbasi, a high-ranking official at the Ministry of Defense was seriously wounded.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] *Wired* speculated that the assassinations could indicate that whoever was behind Stuxnet felt that it was not sufficient to stop the nuclear program.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] That same *Wired* article suggested the Iranian government could have been behind the assassinations.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In January 2010, another Iranian nuclear scientist, a physics professor at Tehran University, was killed in a similar bomb explosion.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 11 January 2012, a director of the Natanz nuclear enrichment facility, Mostafa Ahmadi Roshan, was killed in an attack quite similar to the one that killed Shahriari.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] An analysis by the FAS demonstrates that Iran's enrichment capacity grew during 2010.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The study indicated that Iran's centrifuges appeared to be performing 60% better than in the previous year, which would significantly reduce Tehran's time to produce bomb-grade uranium.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The FAS report was reviewed by an official with the IAEA who affirmed the study.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] European and US officials, along with private experts, told Reuters that Iranian engineers were successful in neutralizing and purging Stuxnet from their country's nuclear machinery.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Given the growth in Iranian enrichment ability in 2010, the country may have intentionally put out misinformation to cause Stuxnet's creators to believe that the worm was more successful in disabling the Iranian nuclear program than it actually was.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Israel, through Unit 8200, has been speculated to be the country behind Stuxnet in multiple media reports and by experts such as Richard A.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Falkenrath, former Senior Director for Policy and Plans within the US Office of Homeland Security.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Israel has not publicly commented on the Stuxnet attack but in 2010 confirmed that cyberwarfare was now among the pillars of its defense doctrine, with a military intelligence unit set up to pursue both defensive and offensive options.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] When questioned whether Israel was behind the virus in the fall of 2010, some Israeli officials broke into "wide smiles", fueling speculation that the government of Israel was involved with its genesis.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] American presidential advisor Gary Samore also smiled when Stuxnet was mentioned, although American officials have suggested that the virus originated abroad.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2009, a year before Stuxnet was discovered, Scott Borg of the United States Cyber-Consequences Unit (US-CCU) suggested that Israel may prefer to mount a cyberattack rather than a military strike on Iran's nuclear facilities.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In late 2010 Borg stated: "Israel certainly has the ability to create Stuxnet and there is little downside to such an attack because it would be virtually impossible to prove who did it.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] So a tool like Stuxnet is Israel's obvious weapon of choice." Iran uses P-1 centrifuges at Natanz, the design for which A.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Khan stole in 1976 and took to Pakistan.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] His black market nuclear-proliferation network sold P-1s to, among other customers, Iran.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Experts believe that Israel also somehow acquired P-1s and tested Stuxnet on the centrifuges, installed at the Dimona facility that is part of its own nuclear program.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The equipment may be from the United States, which received P-1s from Libya's former nuclear program.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Some have also cited several clues in the code such as a concealed reference to the word *MYRTUS*, believed to refer to the Latin name *myrtus* of the Myrtle tree, which in Hebrew is called *hadassah*.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Hadassah was the birth name of the former Jewish queen of Persia, Queen Esther.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] However, it may be that the "MYRTUS" reference is simply a misinterpreted reference to SCADA components known as *RTUs* (Remote Terminal Units) and that this reference is actually "My RTUs"–a management feature of SCADA.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Also, the number 19790509 appears once in the code and may refer to the date *1979 May 09*, the day Habib Elghanian, a Persian Jew, was executed in Tehran.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Another date that appears in the code is "24 September 2007", the day that Iran's president Mahmoud Ahmadinejad spoke at Columbia University and made comments questioning the validity of the Holocaust.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Such data is not conclusive, since, as noted by Symantec, "attackers would have the natural desire to implicate another party".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] There has also been several reports on the involvement of the United States and its collaboration with Israel, with one report stating that "there is vanishingly little doubt that [it] played a role in creating the worm".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] It has been reported that the United States, under one of its most secret programs, initiated by the Bush administration and accelerated by the Obama administration, has sought to destroy Iran's nuclear program by novel methods such as undermining Iranian computer systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] A leaked diplomatic cable showed how the United States was advised to target Iran's nuclear abilities through 'covert sabotage'.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] An article in *The New York Times* in January 2009 credited a then-unspecified program with preventing an Israeli military attack on Iran where some of the efforts focused on ways to destabilize the centrifuges.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] A *Wired* article claimed that Stuxnet "is believed to have been created by the United States".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Dutch historian Peter Koop speculated that the Tailored Access Operations could have developed Stuxnet, possibly in collaboration with Israel.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Bumgarner pointed out that the centrifuges used to process fuel for nuclear weapons are a key target for *cybertage* operations and that they can be made to destroy themselves by manipulating their rotational speeds.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Hayden said: "There are those out there who can take a look at this ... and maybe even attempt to turn it to their own purposes".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In the same report, Sean McGurk, a former cybersecurity official at the Department of Homeland Security noted that the Stuxnet source code could now be downloaded online and modified to be directed at new target systems.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Speaking of the Stuxnet creators, he said: "They opened the box.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In April 2011, Iranian government official Gholam Reza Jalali stated that an investigation had concluded that the United States and Israel were behind the Stuxnet attack.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Frank Rieger stated that three European countries' intelligence agencies agreed that Stuxnet was a joint United States-Israel effort.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The code for the Windows injector and the PLC payload differ in style, likely implying collaboration.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Other experts believe that a US-Israel cooperation is unlikely because "the level of trust between the two countries' intelligence and military establishments is not high".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] A *Wired* magazine article about US General Keith B.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Alexander stated: "And he and his cyber warriors have already launched their first attack.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] China, Jordan, and France are other possibilities, and Siemens may have also participated.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Langner speculated that the infection may have spread from USB drives belonging to Russian contractors since the Iranian targets were not accessible via the Internet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2019, it was reported that an Iranian mole working for Dutch intelligence at the behest of Israel and the CIA inserted the Stuxnet virus with a USB flash drive or convinced another person working at the Natanz facility to do so.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Sandro Gaycken from the Free University Berlin argued that the attack on Iran was a ruse to distract from Stuxnet's real purpose.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to him, its broad dissemination in more than 100,000 industrial plants worldwide suggests a field test of a cyber weapon in different security cultures, testing their preparedness, resilience, and reactions, all highly valuable information for a cyberwar unit.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The United Kingdom has denied involvement in the worm's creation.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In July 2013, Edward Snowden claimed that Stuxnet was cooperatively developed by the United States and Israel.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] According to a report by Reuters, the NSA also tried to sabotage North Korea's nuclear program using a version of Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The operation was reportedly launched in tandem with the attack that targeted Iranian centrifuges in 2009–10.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The North Korean nuclear program shares a number of similarities with the Iranian, both having been developed with technology transferred by Pakistani nuclear scientist A.Q.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The effort failed, however, because North Korea's extreme secrecy and isolation made it impossible to introduce Stuxnet into the nuclear facility.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2018, Gholamreza Jalali, Iran's chief of the National Organization for Passive Defense, claimed that his country fended off a Stuxnet-like attack targeting the country's telecom infrastructure.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Iran's Telecommunications minister, Mohammad-Javad Azari Jahromi has since accused Israel of orchestrating the attack.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Iran plans to sue Israel through the International Court of Justice (ICJ) and is also willing to launch a retaliation attack if Israel does not desist.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] A November 2013 article in Foreign Policy magazine claims existence of an earlier, much more sophisticated attack on the centrifuge complex at Natanz, focused on increasing centrifuge failure rate over a long time period by stealthily inducing uranium hexafluoride gas overpressure incidents.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] This malware was capable of spreading only by being physically installed, probably by previously contaminated field equipment used by contractors working on Siemens control systems within the complex.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] It is not clear whether this attack attempt was successful, but follow-up by a different, simpler, and more conventional attack is indicative that it was not.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 1 September 2011, a new worm was found, thought to be related to Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The Laboratory of Cryptography and System Security (CrySyS) of the Budapest University of Technology and Economics analyzed the malware, naming the threat **Duqu**.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Symantec, based on this report, continued the analysis of the threat, calling it "nearly identical to Stuxnet, but with a completely different purpose", and published a detailed technical paper.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The main component used in Duqu is designed to capture information such as keystrokes and system information.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] The exfiltrated data may be used to enable a future Stuxnet-like attack.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 28 December 2011, Kaspersky Lab's director of global research and analysis spoke to Reuters about recent research results showing that the platform Stuxnet and Duqu both originated in 2007, and is being referred to as Tilded due to the ~d at the beginning of the file names.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Also uncovered in this research was the possibility for three more variants based on the Tilded platform.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In May 2012, the new malware "Flame" was found, thought to be related to Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Researchers named the program "Flame" after the name of one of its modules.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] After analysing the code of Flame, Kaspersky Lab said that there is a strong relationship between Flame and Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] An early version of Stuxnet contained code to propagate infections via USB drives that is nearly identical to a Flame module that exploits the same vulnerability.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Since 2010, there has been extensive international news media coverage on Stuxnet and its aftermath.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In early commentary, *The Economist* pointed out that Stuxnet was "a new kind of cyber-attack".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 8 July 2011, *Wired* then published an article detailing how network security experts were able to decipher the origins of Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In that piece, Kim Zetter claimed that Stuxnet's "cost–benefit ratio is still in question".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Later commentators tended to focus on the strategic significance of Stuxnet as a cyber weapon.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Following the Wired piece, Holger Stark called Stuxnet the "first digital weapon of geopolitical importance, it could change the way wars are fought".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Meanwhile, Eddie Walsh referred to Stuxnet as "the world's newest high-end asymmetric threat".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Ultimately, some claim that the "extensive media coverage afforded to Stuxnet has only served as an advertisement for the vulnerabilities used by various cybercriminal groups".
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] While that may be the case, the media coverage has also increased awareness of cyber security threats.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Alex Gibney's 2016 documentary *Zero Days* covers the phenomenon around Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] A zero-day (also known as 0-day) vulnerability is a computer-software vulnerability that is unknown to, or unaddressed by, those who should be interested in mitigating the vulnerability (including the vendor of the target software).
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Until the vulnerability is mitigated, hackers can exploit it to adversely affect computer programs, data, additional computers or a network.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] In 2016, it was revealed that General James Cartwright, the former head of the U.S.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Strategic Command, had leaked information related to Stuxnet.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] He later pleaded guilty for lying to FBI agents pursuing an investigation into the leak.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] On 17 January 2017, he was granted a full pardon in this case by President Obama, thus expunging his conviction.
[src:industrial-control-security/stuxnet] Darknet Diaries' Podcast episode Stuxnet, discusses Stuxnet with guest Kim Zetter and references the book Count Down to Zero Day.
